entry.content:

Original change's description:

> [display] Propagate change state on display config update

>

> This CL updates OnDidProcessDisplayChanges() to propagate a struct

> of changes to the display configuration. This API is currently only

> implemented by ChromeOS Ash.

>

> There are several DisplayManager methods that modify the existing

> display configuration and these methods can call each other in a

> nested fashion. BeginEndNotifier exists to allow a single call to

> OnWillProcessDisplayChanges() and OnDidProcessDisplayChanges() on

> either side of an atomic change in display configuration state.

>

> This CL introduces DisplayManager::PendingDisplayChanges which is

> intended to track all display config changes that occur before

> the last BeginEndNotifier falls out of scope. At this time

> this is translated to a DisplayConfigurationChange struct more

> appropriate for observers and propagated in the call to

> OnDidProcessDisplayChanges().

>

> This CL also adds a test to ensure what is propagated by

> the DisplayManagerObserver is consistent with what is propagated by

> the DisplayObserver.

>

> Follow up CLs will also

> - update exo to leverage this as a means to consume an atomic

> update to the display configuration state.

>

> - consolidate the other existing mechanisms that communicate

> display configuration changes. For e.g. see

> DisplayManager::Delegate::Pre[Post]DisplayConfigurationChange()

> and downstream methods.

>

> - update clients that rely on other means to infer display

> configuration changes (using OnDisplayAdded[Removed]() for e.g.)

entry.title: Log previewed and selected image quality for wallpaper search
entry.content:
This requires two changes to how we manage log entries:

(1) We may have to hold on to log entries from previous requests since

whether am image was selected as the background when the session

ends is only known then. For simplicity, we just hold on to all log

entries and mark the selected one if necessary on session close.

(2) We store a link to the image quality entry in the result set map.

Images are identified by a token. By storing a link we can map a

token to both the image and its associated image quality entry.

entry.title: Introduce SkipTPCDMitigationsWithAdsHeuristic feature
entry.content:
Introduces a disabled by default feature which allows skipping

TPCD mitigation checks when the cookie access is tagged as being used

for advertising purposes.



This means that cookies will continue to be blocked for cookie accesses

on ad requests even if the 3PC mitigations would otherwise allow the

access.



This is integrated via a new set of CookieSettingOverrides.



Each individual mitigation is given an override and an equivalent

feature param to allow more flexibility.

called in SafetyCheckObserverBridge's destructor.

`SafetyCheckManagerObserver`, notifying observers to reset their

`SafetyCheckManagerObserver` observations at the correct time.

entry.title: SQL: Ensure CorruptSizeInHeader is using exclusive mode
entry.content:
The corruptSizeInHeader function is used in unittests to

corrupt the database on disk.



If the database is opened in WAL, it requires a checkpoint to

ensures the data is moved from the journal to the actual database

(a.k.a sqlite3_wal_checkpoint_v2(...)).



This CL is ensuring the database is opened in exclusive mode;

which means there is no other opened instance of that database.

If there was instances, CorruptSizeInHeader(...) will fail and

return false. The corresponding unittests will fail and should be

fixed.

entry.title: Don't include disabled types in the supported types
entry.content:
FormGroup::GetSupportedTypes() return a ServerFieldTypeSet indicating

for which ServerFieldTypes the group can store values. This is used

to determine for which types the FormGroup should vote.



When new types are introduced behind a feature flag, they are generally

only exposed through GetSupportedTypes() when that feature flag is

enabled (example [1]).

For new types added as part of the i18n efforts, this is not the case.

This could potentially be a problem during voting, if a user is enrolled

in an experiment, stores data for such a type and then unenrolls from

the experiment, e.g. by restarting the browser. In this case, that

client would continue sending votes.



This CL fixes this problem by overriding AddressComponent::GetTypes()

in FeatureGuardedAddressComponent, similar to the logic that prevents

storing data in the address component when the feature flag is disabled.



[1] https://source.chromium.org/chromium/chromium/src/+/main:components/autofill/core/browser/data_model/phone_number.cc;l=78;drc=75352e2f484c44c9b4d1f5f9ee827471d4869741

entry.title: Move from third_party.toml to cargo-centered approach for 3p rust
entry.content:
The //third_party/rust/chromium_crates_io dir now acts like a cargo

project that provides a crates.io mirror of the crates we use in the

Chromium project.



We generate GN files out of the chromium_crates_io dir into the same

places under //third_party/rust.



This moves to using mostly the same codepaths in gnrt for 3p rust

crates as for stdlib.

- third_party.toml has moved to chromium_crates_io/Cargo.toml

- Cargo.lock has moved to chromium_crates_io/

- `gnrt gen` now builds from chromium_crates_io/Cargo.toml but writes

the BUILD.gn files to the same place.

- `gnrt download` will now do the wrong thing and needs to be removed

or replaced by `cargo vendor` or something else like it.

- Added gnrt_config.toml for 3p crates along with a few flags specific

to 3p crates: allow_first_party_usage, build_script_outputs, group.

- Added remove_build_rs config to avoid having to patch out the

build.rs file in cxx.

- Patches are all moved to //third_party/rust/chromium_crates_io/patches

- Crates only for test are now marked `testonly` in GN, instead of

only applying that to the `test_support` group alias.



The old 3p code paths for generating GN rules in gnrt are left

behind, and are now unused. They will be deleted in a follow up

CL.



The gen.rs function for generated stdlib was forked for generating

3p, but all other functions are shared. More code could be merged

in future CLs.



Next steps:

- Move the GN files from //third_party/rust/X to

//third_party/rust/{safe,sandbox,test}/X (and move the

README.chromium files over)

- Throw errors if a safe crate depends on a sandbox crate.

- Run `cargo vendor` and update crates as a result (we're behind in

ways Cargo does not like at the moment, even with fixed versions

specified). Add `.cargo/config` to point cargo at the `vendor/`

directory for crates. Remove all the crates-io patches in

`Cargo.toml`.

- A script to re-apply all the patches in `patches/` to `vendor/`.

entry.title: [base] Split RunOnceCb<> -> RunOnceCb<> & RunOnceCbRepeatedly<>
entry.content:
The enable_if_t condition introduced in https://crrev.com/c/2379840

relies on std::is_copy_constructible for dispatching to move/copy

overloads of RunOnceCallbackImpl; however, std::is_copy_constructible

always returns true for std::vector (and subsequently for

std::tuple>) which ultimately leads to compilation

failures when the incorrect overload is selected.



This CL ensures a clearer separation between the move- and copy- use

cases by means of splitting the API into two different functions.

entry.title: Improve A11y Announcement of Content Settings.
entry.content:
Currently, on the category settings pages, each toggle has a title (e.g.

Location) and a subtitle (e.g. Ask before allowing sites to know your

location), with the subtitle changing when the toggle is switched (e.g. to Blocked).



This is not great for accessibility. This CL changes leaves the visible UI unchanged, but changes screen reader announcements such that we announce both states of this toggle at once as two full sentences. This announcement is then followed by the ON/OFF announcement corresponding to the actual toggle state.
